\begin_layout Standard
And the expected number of ``unbirthdays'' of all students is, since there
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 days in a year,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
U & = & D\times P_{N}\\
 & \approx & De^{-\alpha}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, in an ordinary year(in contrast to the leap year) 
\begin_inset Formula $D=365$
\end_inset

, and in a school where there are 30 classes and in average 36.5 students
 every class, 
\begin_inset Formula $N=1095$
\end_inset

 students, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=3$
\end_inset

, therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{N} & = & e^{-3}\approx\frac{1}{20},\\
U & \approx & 365\times e^{-3}\\
 & \approx & \unit[18.17]{days}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So even in an ordinary `biggish' school it si quite probabble that there
 are quite a few all-students' unbirthdays left over.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the expected number of all students' unbirthday should be under 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
U & \approx & De^{-\alpha}<d,\\
D/d & < & e^{\alpha},\\
\ln\frac{D}{d} & < & \alpha=\frac{N}{D},\\
\therefore N & > & D\ln\frac{D}{d}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

That is, for example, if the expected number of all students' unbirthdays
 should be less than 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>5.9$
\end_inset

 and the student number 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 should be larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $2153$
\end_inset

.
 
